<https://doi.org/10.15468/JXUSK2> <http://purl.org/dc/terms/language> <http://publications.europa.eu/resource/authority/language/ENG>;
    <http://purl.org/dc/terms/publisher> <https://www.gbif.se>;
    <http://purl.org/dc/terms/description> "The NILS Inventory 2003–2020 is the original NILS landscape monitoring programme, conducted from 2003 to 2020, and encompassed all terrestrial environments in Sweden, including both lowland and alpine areas (lowland until 2018; alpine until 2020). The programme was established to monitor biodiversity across the Swedish landscape and to track long-term changes in the everyday landscape. A central component was to assess changes in landscape composition and structure, and the prerequisites for biodiversity.\n\nIn years 2003–2018 data were collected nationwide, from 2019-2020 data collection continued only in alpine areas.\n\nThe true coordinates of the permanent sample plots are protected. The coordinates in this dataset are generalised, by randomly offsetting true coordinates with 200-2000 m. See also Additional Information.\n\nThe original NILS Inventory has been replaced and extended by five separate inventories specifically adapted to the different landscape types: the NILS Alpine Inventory (initiated 2021), NILS Deciduous Forest Inventory (initiated 2020), NILS Grassland Inventory (initiated 2020), NILS Wetland Inventory (initiated 2023) and the THUF Seashore Inventory (initiated 2012). Data from those inventories will be published in separate datasets and can currently be accessed only directly from the organisation."@en;
    a <http://www.w3.org/ns/dcat#Dataset>
}

<feed> <https://w3id.org/tree#member> <#39794814885978e4e0c6994fe3fd7072>.
<#39794814885978e4e0c6994fe3fd7072> a <https://www.w3.org/ns/activitystreams#Create>;
    <https://www.w3.org/ns/activitystreams#object> <https://doi.org/10.23695/VKPG-1843>;
    <https://www.w3.org/ns/activitystreams#published> "2026-03-12T06:18:37.821Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime>.
<#39794814885978e4e0c6994fe3fd7072> {
<https://doi.org/10.23695/VKPG-1843> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dcat#keyword> "Language Technology (Computational Linguistics)"@en, "corpus"@en;
    <http://www.w3.org/ns/dcat#distribution> <https://doi.org/10.23695/VKPG-1843#distribution>;
    <http://purl.org/dc/terms/issued> "2025-11-07T00:00:00Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime>;
    <http://www.w3.org/ns/dcat#landingPage> <https://doi.org/10.23695/VKPG-1843>;
    <http://purl.org/dc/terms/modified> "2026-02-20T00:00:00Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime>;
    <http://purl.org/dc/terms/title> "Funeral Sermons from Skokloster palace's library"@en, "Likpredikningar från Skokloster slotts bibliotek"@sv;
    <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#qualifiedAttribution> _:b0__7875.
_:b0__7875 <http://www.w3.org/ns/dcat#hadRole> <http://inspire.ec.europa.eu/metadata-codelist/ResponsiblePartyRole/author>;
    <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#agent> <https://admin.dataportal.se/store/818/resource/22039c963ea2299d30d38116bde04643>;
    a <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#Attribution>.
<https://doi.org/10.23695/VKPG-1843> <http://purl.org/dc/terms/language> <http://publications.europa.eu/resource/authority/language/SWE>;
    <http://purl.org/dc/terms/publisher> <http://dataportal.se/organisation/SE2021003153>;
    <http://purl.org/dc/terms/description> "SKOLIK refers to a collection of just over 1,000 printed funeral sermons from the 17th and 18th centuries\nheld in the library of Skokloster Castle. With funding from the Riksbankens Jubileumsfond, the collection\nhas been digitized within the framework of the project Från bokskåpet till skärmen. Digitalisering av\nlikpredikningarna i Skoklosters slottsbibliotek, a collaboration between Stockholm University and the\nNational Historical Museums. Funeral sermons are a valuable source for understanding life in early modern\nEurope. The fact that nearly half of the sermons concern women—who are otherwise strongly underrepresented\nin the archives—makes the collection particularly significant.\nThe transcribed texts from the SKOLIK project are now available in Korp. The corpus will be updated as\nadditional material from the collection of funeral sermons at Skokloster Castle is transcribed.\nSearch the collection on the National Historical Museums’\nwebsite\nor read more about SKOLIK on the project\nwebsite."@en, "SKOLIK syftar på en samling av drygt 1000 tryckta likpredikningar från 1600- och 1700-talet som finns i\nSkoklosters slottsbibliotek. Samlingen har med stöd från Riksbankens jubileumsfond digitaliserats inom ramen\nför projektet Från bokskåpet till skärmen. Digitalisering av likpredikningarna i Skoklosters\nslottsbibliotek, ett samarbete mellan Stockholms universitet och Statens historiska museer. Likpredikningar\när en värdefull källa för förståelsen av livet i Europa under tidigmodern tid. Att nästan hälften av\npredikningarna behandlar kvinnor som annars är starkt underrepresenterade i arkiven, gör samlingen särskilt\nrelevant.\nDe transkriberade texterna från SKOLIK-projektet finns nu tillgängliga i Korp. Korpusen kommer att\nuppdateras i takt med att ytterligare material ur samlingen av likpredikningar på Skoklosters slott\ntranskriberas.\nSök i samlingen på Statens historiska museers\nwebbplats\neller läs mer om SKOLIK på projektets\nwebbplats."@sv;
    a <http://www.w3.org/ns/dcat#Dataset>
}

